Using advanced algorithms and a scan with resolution high enough to fully separate the structures of interest, it is possible to automatically and non-destructively acquire and quantify various kinds of morphometric data for every single structure, e.g. a zooidal or avicularian chamber, which would be extremely difficult using conventional methods. We demonstrate the possibility of automatically calculating the size and volume of the zooidal and avicularian chambers, as well as the diameter of rhizoidal tubules. Using any of the measurements in the micro-CT dataset, it was possible to distinguish between zooidal and avicularian chambers in Smittina imragueni n. sp. (
). Furthermore, we could separate two classes of openings in the frontal shield, viz. orifices and frontal pores (
), which concurred well with the dimensions observed on SEM micrographs. Differences between the mean values for external zooidal length and the length of the zooidal chamber in S. imragueni n. sp. resulted from the overlapping of the proximal parts of succeeding zooids with the distal part of preceding ones.

A limitation results from a small ratio between the resolution of the CT-scan and the size of the feature under examination, which might lead to incomplete recording or failure of thin and/or fragile skeletal structures, as we encountered in C. bafouri n. sp. In that case, the distinct but not very pronounced size differences between the opesiae and rhizoidal pores, observed with SEM, were not reproduced by the CT appraisal (
). Another example was the orifice and frontal-pore measurements in S. imragueni n. sp. (
), for which some data points plotted in an intermediate position between the orifice and frontal pores. These outlying measurements were certainly caused by incompletely resolved orifices and frontal pores. In addition, this species highlights the influence of the quality of the original CT-scan data on subsequent analyses. Owing to the comparatively low acceleration voltage of the SEM, the recording of the inner calcification was too poor for automatic detection of the zooidal chambers, and time-consuming manual correction was necessary. However,
Klicpera et al . ( 2013 )
used the same micro-CT system to describe another Recent cheilostome with satisfying results, highlighting that even smaller CT-systems can achieve results with very high resolution. In that case, however, the membraniporid species investigated was significantly more weakly calcified and smaller in zooid size than the specimens we investigated.

Environmental preferences of the new bryozoan species. Both new species belong to relatively speciose genera with global distributions, ranging from tropical to polar waters, and representatives of both genera are known from adjacent regions south and north of the area we investigated ( Canu & Bassler 1925 , 1928 ; Cook 1968 , 1985 ;
Aristegui & Cruz 1986 ). Despite the lower frequency of occurrence of S. imragueni n. sp. , both species appear to have generally similar habitat preferences, living specimens occurring on mound tops, mound flanks, in canyons and on canyon shoulders (
Table 1 ;
). Temperatures ranged from 9 to 12 ° C, salinity from 35.2 to 35.5 psu, and oxygen concentration from 0.92 ml l - 1 to 1.54 ml l - 1 . The first two parameters are in the normal range for bryozoans, especially in light of the global distribution of both genera. Oxygen saturation, however, was remarkably low, and close to dysoxic levels (
Rhoads & Morse 1971 ;
Levin 2003 ). As bryozoans lack any dedicated respiratory organs, oxygen uptake is relatively ineffective and takes place via simple diffusion (
Ryland 1967 ). Bryozoans are active filter feeders with low metabolic costs in general, although there are considerable interspecific differences in oxygen consumption, representing fundamentally different metabolic strategies in different species (
Peck & Barnes 2004 ). Lophophore activity, i.e. feeding, consumes only a minor amount of energy, while most energy appears to be used for growth, reproduction and polypide regeneration (
Peck & Barnes 2004 ). Colonies of C. bafouri n. sp. frequently bore fertile zooids, and S. imragueni exhibited strong secondary calcification, both of which can be considered to be highly energy-demanding. Thus, adaptation to low oxygen concentrations is evident. A possible way in which these species reduce their energy consumption might be slow growth. Intracellular digestion by the bryozoan gut is also quite ineffective (
Dewel et al . 2002 ), necessitating a high supply of food particles (
Taylor 2000 ). This high nutritional demand is met in waters off Mauritania by increased primary productivity resulting from the strong upwelling regime. Food particles are exported from surface waters to greater depths, thus reducing the energy required to satisfy the bryozoans’ nutritional demands, because less oxygen is required to capture the same quantity of food.
